### Some notation for neural networks

The following concepts are standard, introduced mostly to clarify notation. Let \(f:\mathbb{R}^{n}\times\mathbb{R}^{d}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{k}\) with \((\bm{x},\bm{\theta})\mapsto f(\bm{x};\bm{\theta})\) be a model with input, output, and parameter spaces \(\mathbb{R}^{n}\), \(\mathbb{R}^{k}\), \(\mathbb{R}^{d}\). Let \(\mathcal{D}:=\{(\bm{x}_{i},\bm{y}_{i})\}_{i=1}^{m}\) be a dataset and write \(\bm{X}:=\{\bm{x}_{i}\}_{i=1}^{m}\) and \(\bm{Y}:=\{\bm{y}_{i}\}_{i=1}^{m}\). We moreover write \(f(\bm{X};\bm{\theta}):=\operatorname{vec}(\{f(\bm{x}_{i};\bm{\theta})\}_{i=1 }^{m})\in\mathbb{R}^{mk}\). The standard way of training \(f\) is by finding a point \(\bm{\theta}^{*}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\) s.t. \(\bm{\theta}^{*}=\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\bm{\theta}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}\sum_{ i=1}^{m}\ell(\bm{y}_{i},f(\bm{x}_{i};\bm{\theta}))=:\operatorname*{arg\,min} _{\bm{\theta}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}\mathcal{L}(\bm{\theta})\), for some loss function \(\ell\). If we add a weight decay \(\gamma/2\|\bm{\theta}\|_{2}^{2}\) term to \(\mathcal{L}(\bm{\theta})\), the minimization problem has a probabilistic interpretation as _maximum a posteriori_ (MAP) estimation of the posterior density \(p(\bm{\theta}\mid\mathcal{D})\) under the likelihood function \(p(\bm{Y}\mid f(\bm{X};\bm{\theta}))\propto\exp(-\sum_{i=1}^{m}\ell(\bm{y}_{i}, f(\bm{x}_{i};\bm{\theta})))\) and an isotropic Gaussian prior \(p(\bm{\theta})=\mathcal{N}(\bm{\theta}\mid\bm{0},\gamma^{-1}\bm{I})\). We denote the MAP loss by \(\mathcal{L}_{\text{MAP}}\). In our present context, this interpretation is relevant because this probabilistic interpretation implies a probability density, and it is widely known that a probability density transforms nontrivially under reparametrization.

A textbook way of obtaining \(\bm{\theta}^{*}\) is gradient descent (GD): At each time step \(t\), obtain the next estimate \(\bm{\theta}^{(t+1)}=\bm{\theta}^{(t)}-\alpha\bm{\nabla}\mathcal{L}|_{\bm{ \theta}^{(t)}}\), for some \(\alpha>0\). This can be considered as the discretization of the gradient flow ODE \(\dot{\bm{\theta}}=-\bm{\nabla}\mathcal{L}|_{\bm{\theta}}\). Among the many variants of GD is preconditioned GD which considers a positive-definite matrix field \(\bm{R}\) on \(\mathbb{R}^{d}\), yielding \(\dot{\bm{\theta}}=-\bm{R}(\bm{\theta})^{-1}\,\bm{\nabla}\mathcal{L}|_{\bm{ \theta}}\).

### The geometry of the parameter space

**Remark 1**.: We restrict our discussion to global coordinate charts since they are the default assumption in neural networks, and in a bid to make our discussion clear for people outside of the differential geometry community. We refer the curious reader to Appendix D for a discussion on local coordinate charts. Note that, our results hold in the general local-chart formulation. \(\blacksquare\)

The parameter space \(\mathbb{R}^{d}\) is the canonical example of a smooth manifold. We can impose upon this manifold a (global) coordinate chart: a homeomorphism that represents a point with an element of \(\mathbb{R}^{d}\). The standard choice is the Cartesian coordinate system \(\theta:\mathbb{R}^{d}\rightarrow\Theta\cong\mathbb{R}^{d}\), which we have used in the previous section. That is, the image of \(\theta\) uniquely represents elements of \(\mathbb{R}^{d}\)--given a point \(z\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\), we write \(\bm{\theta}=\theta(z)\) for its coordinate representation under \(\theta\).

The choice of a coordinate system is not unique. Any homeomorphism \(\psi:\mathbb{R}^{d}\rightarrow\Psi\cong\mathbb{R}^{d}\) can be used as an alternative coordinate chart. For instance, the polar coordinates can be used to represent points in \(\mathbb{R}^{d}\) instead. Crucially, the images of any pair of coordinates must be connected through a diffeomorphism (a smooth function with a smooth inverse) \(\varphi:\Theta\rightarrow\Psi\). Such a map is called a _change of coordinates_ or _reparametrization_ since it acts on the parameter space.

**Example 2** (Reparametrization).: Reparametrization is ubiquitous in machine learning:

1. _Mean-Field Variational Inference._ Let \(q(\bm{x};\bm{\theta})\) be a variational approximation, which is often chosen to be \(\mathcal{N}(\bm{x}\mid\bm{\mu},\operatorname{diag}(\bm{\sigma}^{2}))\), i.e. \(\bm{\theta}=\{\bm{\mu}\in\mathbb{R}^{d},\bm{\sigma}^{2}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}_{>0}\}\). Common choices of reparametrization of \(\bm{\sigma}^{2}\) include the log-space [52] or softplus [12] parametrization.
2. _Weight normalization._ Given a NN \(f_{\bm{\theta}}\), WeightNorm [69] applies the reparametrization \(\bm{\psi}=r\bm{\eta}\) where \(r\in\mathbb{R}_{>0}\) and \(\bm{\eta}:=\bm{\theta}/\|\bm{\theta}\|\in\mathbb{S}^{d-1}\). This is akin to the polar coordinates. (Note that we assume \(\bm{\theta}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\setminus\{\bm{0}\}\) since otherwise \(\varphi\) is not a global diffeomorphism.) \(\blacksquare\)

At each point \(z\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\), there exists a vector space \(T_{z}\mathbb{R}^{d}\) called the _tangent space at \(z\)_, consisting of the so-called _tangent vectors_. An important example of a tangent vector is the gradient vector \(\operatorname{grad}\mathcal{L}|_{z}\)

