## Appendix A A Simple Working Example

Let \(\Theta:=\mathbb{R}^{d}\) and let \(\mathcal{L}:\mathbb{R}^{d}\to\mathbb{R}\) defined by \(\mathcal{L}(\bm{\theta}):=\sum_{i=1}^{d}(\bm{\theta}_{i})^{2}\) be a twice-differentiable function on \(\Theta\). Suppose \(\varphi:\Theta\to\Psi\) defined by \(\varphi(\bm{\theta})=3\bm{\theta}=:\bm{\psi}\) be the reparametrization of choice. In this example, we shall see how this often-used reparametrization leads to pathologies in the values derived from the Hessian of \(\mathcal{L}\) computed by an autodiff system.

Notice that the Jacobian of \(\varphi\) is given by \(\bm{J}(\bm{\theta})=\operatorname{diag}(3,\ldots,3)\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times d}\) and its inverse is \(\bm{J}^{-1}(\bm{\psi})=\operatorname{diag}(\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}},\ldots, \nicefrac{{1}}{{3}})\). The autodiff Hessian matrix is given by \(\bm{H}(\bm{\theta})\equiv 2\bm{I}\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times d}\). When we transform \(\bm{\theta}\to\bm{\psi}\), the function \(\mathcal{L}(\bm{\theta})\) becomes \(\hat{\mathcal{L}}(\bm{\psi}):=\sum_{i=1}^{d}(\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}}\bm{\psi}_{i })^{2}\). The autodiff will take into account this change and thus will compute the Hessian \(\hat{\bm{H}}\) of \(\hat{\mathcal{L}}\) as

\[\hat{\bm{H}}_{ij}(\bm{\psi})=\operatorname{diag}(\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}},\ldots, \nicefrac{{1}}{{3}})\,(2\bm{I})\operatorname{diag}(\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}},\ldots, \nicefrac{{1}}{{3}})=\operatorname{diag}(\nicefrac{{2}}{{9}},\ldots, \nicefrac{{2}}{{9}}).\]

Notice that, \(\det\bm{H}(\bm{\theta})\equiv 2^{d}\), meanwhile, we have \(\det\hat{\bm{H}}(\bm{\psi})\equiv(\nicefrac{{2}}{{9}})^{d}\). Therefore, the Hessian determinant computed by an autodiff system is not invariant under reparametrization.

But if instead we explicitly take into account the metric into the Hessian, which by default is (implicitly) chosen to be \(\bm{G}(\bm{\theta})\equiv\bm{I}\), resulting in the seemingly redundant expression \(\bm{E}(\bm{\theta})=\bm{G}(\bm{\theta})^{-1}\bm{H}(\bm{\theta})=\bm{I}^{-1} (2\bm{I})\), and perform the correct transformation on both identity matrices, we obtain

\[\hat{\bm{E}}(\bm{\psi}) =(\operatorname{diag}(\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}},\ldots,\nicefrac{{1}} {{3}})\,\bm{I}\operatorname{diag}(\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}},\ldots,\nicefrac{{1}} {{3}}))^{-1}\operatorname{diag}(\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}},\ldots,\nicefrac{{1}}{{3 }})\,(2\bm{I})\operatorname{diag}(\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}},\ldots,\nicefrac{{1}} {{3}})\] \[=\operatorname{diag}(3,\ldots,3)\,\underline{\operatorname{diag} (\nicefrac{{3}}{{3}},\ldots,\nicefrac{{3}}{{3}})}\,\underline{\operatorname{ diag}(\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}},\ldots,\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}})}\,(2\bm{I})\operatorname{diag}( \nicefrac{{1}}{{3}},\ldots,\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}})\] \[=\operatorname{diag}(3,\ldots,3)\,(2\bm{I})\operatorname{diag}( \nicefrac{{1}}{{3}},\ldots,\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}}).\]

Thus, the determinant of the transformed "metric-conditioned Hessian" equals

\[\det\hat{\bm{E}}(\bm{\psi})=(\det\operatorname{diag}(3,\ldots,3))\,(\det 2\bm{I})( \det\operatorname{diag}(\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}},\ldots,\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}}))=3^{d }2^{d}(\nicefrac{{1}}{{3}})^{d}=2^{d},\]

which coincides with the determinant of the original \(\bm{E}\).

