In the matrix form, we can write the above as \(\tilde{\bm{H}}=\bm{J}^{-\top}\bm{H}\bm{J}^{-1}\), where \(\bm{J}\) is the Jacobian of \(\varphi\). Thus, the Riemannian Hessian at any \(\bm{\theta}\) (not just at critical points) transforms just like the metric and thus invariant as discussed in Example 4. Note: this only holds when the term containing the connection coefficients \(\bm{\Gamma}^{k}_{ij}\) is explicitly considered. In particular, the Euclidean Hessian does not follow this tensorial transformation under autodiff due to the fact that (i) \(\bm{\Gamma}^{k}_{ij}=0\) for any \(i\), \(j\), \(k\) and thus dropped from the equation, _and_ (ii) autodiff is not designed to handle advanced geometric objects like \(\bm{\Gamma}^{k}_{ij}\).

### Hessian-Trace Under Reparametrization

Let \(\mathcal{L}:\mathbb{R}^{d}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}\) be a function of \(\mathbb{R}^{d}\) under the Cartesian coordinates and \(\bm{G}\) a Riemannian metric. The _Riemannian trace_ of the Hessian matrix \(\bm{H}\) of \(\mathcal{L}\) is defined by [47]:

\[(\mathrm{tr}_{\bm{G}}\,\bm{H})(\bm{\theta})=\mathrm{tr}(\bm{G}(\bm{\theta})^{-1 }\bm{H}(\bm{\theta})).\] (9)

That is, it is defined as the standard trace of the Hessian operator \(\bm{E}\).

Let \(\varphi:\bm{\theta}\mapsto\bm{\psi}\) be a reparametrization on \(\mathbb{R}^{d}\). Then, using (2) and the property \(\mathrm{tr}(\bm{A}\bm{B})=\mathrm{tr}(\bm{B}\bm{A})\) twice, the Riemannian trace of the Hessian transforms into

\[\begin{split}(\mathrm{tr}_{\tilde{\bm{G}}}\,\tilde{\bm{H}})(\bm{ \psi})&=\mathrm{tr}(\tilde{\bm{E}}(\bm{\psi}))\\ &=\mathrm{tr}((\bm{J}^{-1}(\bm{\psi}))^{-1}\bm{G}(\varphi^{-1}( \bm{\psi}))\bm{H}(\varphi^{-1}(\bm{\psi}))\bm{J}^{-1}(\bm{\psi}))\\ &=\mathrm{tr}(\bm{G}(\varphi^{-1}(\bm{\psi}))\bm{H}(\varphi^{-1}( \bm{\psi})))\\ &=(\mathrm{tr}_{\bm{G}}\,\bm{H})(\varphi^{-1}(\bm{\psi})).\end{split}\] (10)

Since \(\bm{\psi}=\varphi(\bm{\theta})\), we have that \((\mathrm{tr}_{\tilde{\bm{G}}}\,\tilde{\bm{H}})(\bm{\psi})=(\mathrm{tr}_{\bm{G}}\, \bm{H})(\bm{\theta})\) for any given \(\bm{\theta}\). Therefore, the trace of the Hessian operator (or the Riemannian trace of the Hessian) is invariant.

